The paper discusses the use of convolutional neural networks (CNNs) for EEG-based brain computer interfaces (BCIs), which involves signal processing, machine learning, and human-computer interaction. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). The paper also introduces a new CNN architecture for EEG-based BCIs, which involves model design and optimization, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) another likely category. Additionally, the paper applies CNNs to EEG signals, which involves image processing and computer vision concepts, making cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) a possible category. The paper also discusses the interpretation of learned features, which involves explainable AI, making cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) another possible category. Finally, the paper discusses the application of BCIs for human-computer interaction, making cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction) a possible category as well.
